    *   Luis M. Contreras asked the chairs if a liaison reply should be sent back to 3GPP. Pawan Beeram agreed a reply is appropriate and stated they will coordinate with the liaison manager.

### 6. Applicability of IETF-Defined Service and Network Data Models for Network Slice Service Management
*   **Presenter:** Luis M. Contreras
*   **Slides:** [06 Applicability of IETF-Defined Service and Network Data Models for Network Slice Service Management](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-teas-06-applicability-of-ietf-defined-service-and-network-data-models-for-network-slice-service-management-00)
*   **Draft:** `draft-ietf-teas-ns-models-applicability`
*   **Discussion:**
    *   The draft defines the mapping of slice service model parameters to existing service and network models (e.g., L3SM, L2SM, L3NM, L2NM).
    *   Recent updates focused on functional and capability alignment (e.g., SLA templates, connection groups, custom topologies, and performance monitoring) to identify gaps that might require extensions in those models.
    *   The authors plan to add multi-domain realization examples and solicit feedback from the mailing list.
    *   Regarding a potential home for this document, Luis M. Contreras noted prior discussions about transferring it to the OPSAWG. Pawan Beeram advised continuing the work within TEAS for now, as no formal discussions have occurred with OPSAWG yet. Oscar González de Dios noted that the upcoming OPSAWG session would be a good opportunity to discuss this.

### 7. ACTN Extensions for Inter-Operator Coordination
*   **Presenter:** Takeo Miyasaka
*   **Slides:** [14 ACTN Extensions for Inter-Operator Coordination](https://datatracker.ietf.org/meeting/126/materials/slides-126-teas-14-actn-extensions-for-inter-operator-coordination-00)
*   This is a new, individual zero-zero draft exploring how to extend ACTN to support multi-operator, multi-administrative-domain environments. It introduces an MDSC-to-MDSC interface (MMI) to allow independent operators to share abstracted topologies and jointly establish end-to-end TE paths (e.g., for AI data center interconnections).
*   **Discussion:**
    *   Daniel King asked how this work relates to the Metro Ethernet Forum (MEF) LSO (Lifecycle Service Orchestration) APIs (like Legato), which aim to coordinate resources across providers. He questioned if MEF's work was deemed insufficient. Takeo Miyasaka responded that they are starting a gap analysis of MEF LSO to be included in the next version.
    *   Dhruv Dhody noted that the original ACTN architecture assumed multi-operator coordination could be handled by having one operator's MDSC act as a CNC to another operator's MDSC. He suggested clearly defining the trust boundaries and technical distinctions between a standard multi-domain network and independent cooperative operators before designing new interfaces.
    *   Daniele Ceccarelli questioned the real-world applicability of the data center use case, noting that operators rarely deploy MDSCs in data centers.
    *   Italo Busi suggested looking at Figure 10 of RFC 8453 (referred to as 8345 in the transcript), which depicts an MDSC acting as a CNC, to evaluate why that existing model is insufficient for the draft's use cases.

